review_blob: Probs my fav of the Leffe line that Ive tried. Happy to see after the years this started showing up in the States more often.
Draft at Bottleworks last week. Think of a thicker a darker Rodenbach, bit more soured all around. Fucking good brew.
Bottle. Pretty middle of the road pale for me, even for Founders. Dont taste the dry hopping so much, but the malt profile is strong with this one. Good session beer.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: 375ml. Purchased in Eugene, OR a few years back. Drank November 2015. Jet black pour, little head. Lightly spiced up nose with hints of bourbon and dark cocoa beneath. Flavor is raisiny up front, while bringing in the cocoa in the mid-palate, hinting at the cinammon and spice blended with bourbon and a tiny bit of heat in the back. Id imagine this one being HOT fresh after bottling. Glad I waited a few years. Thick, dank.
beer_name: Lost Abbey Box Set: Track #8 (Number of the Beast)

review_blob: 2013 2nd Batch 375ml bottle drank in November 2015. Aroma of fainted barnyard funk, hints of hay, and a light and delicate nod at plums. Flavors have similar notes of the nose, a very round barnyard funk, hay, and hints and nods at plum and apples. A sour acid coats the tongue beautifully. Two years has done pleasant things to this one. Very tart, nice carbonation. Lovely.

Purchased from The Beer Junction, Seattle, WA May this year. Bottle 149/240. Had one of those feelings I shouldve bought more than one of these when I had the chance. This was one of those spectacular beer experiences a geek like yourself would enjoy. Fairly bourbony on the nose with hints of tropical fruit and a bit of red wine. Flavors are abound in every direction with notes of vanilla, oak, pinot, tropical fruits tossed with hops, pineapple, and a singe of hoppy bitterness in the finish blended with bourbon alcohol. Fucking brilliant and beautiful. Wish I had more!!!!

On tap at the brewery a couple months back. Epic nose on this one, hints of citra hop surrounded by hints of barnyard and hay, little hint of sour bacteria. The sour comes out more in the mid-palate, with a very creamy feel from the lacto. Citra and saisonish flavors meet brilliantly in the middle for a tart and refreshing dip of a Berliner.

12oz. Said it before, Ill say it again: love the wave of blood orange IPAs happening right now. This fits the bill properly as well bringing a nice tartness to the center of the palate. Good stuff, wish it was as pricey as it is for a 6er...
beer_name: Flying Dog Bloodline Blood Orange IPA

review_blob: 12oz. No head (thats what she said!) Booze, vanilla, coconut, and wet cocoa on the nose. Dark fruits...sweetly roasted? Rum, coconut husk, hints of leather, sweetness, godsdamn this is a keeper! Boozey finish, lingers. Somehow a bit light even though this bottle says 12%. And by light just not so thick. Creamy.
12oz. Is what it is - Prairies version of a 6er beer - and its dank. Full on sessionable saison here. Grainy, slight hay, hints of spice. Excellent for what it is.

12oz. Brownish see through color with little head. Notes of vanilla, sweet malts, and sugar on the nose. Palate has raisins, dark plums, Belgian candi sugar, molasses, toffee, and dank written all over it. Big bourbony finish. Little watery throughout, but it works. This bottle is labeled at 12% ABV. Drank today and bought today 8/18/15.

Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Big booze wet JD nose with hints of spice underneath. The Bifrost is definitely still recognizable on the palate as the JD more paints over it lightly. Nice vanilla oakd finish. Pretty good.

Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Totally forgot we had this on the shelf at the BW for a while back then. I liked it. It was the best thing ever, but it held fairly well and tasted great after a year +.
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Big roasty sweet nose through a jet black pour. Sweet in the dark fruit range up front with cocoa and sugary roast in the back. Yum!
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Lots of big floral notes at first with a lovely pined out rush in the back. Lingering bitterness.
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Light, not much going on here. Think its their homage to light beer to drink with watching sports...
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Had this a few times after over the years. Straight up Irish stout, thinner and creamy smooth, especially through nitro.
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Looks like theyre actually still making this one too. Big sweet malts with hints of molasses and some dark fruits. Same on palate. Pretty good.
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Big jasmine nose, lots of heavy malts. Bits of hoppy goodness behind. Pretty good.
beer_name: Elysian Avatar Jasmine IPA - Brew 2000 Imperial

review_blob: Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Looked good on paper. Wasnt as good on the palate. The ideas were there, just a bit watered down with malts.
330ml bottle. This series can pretty much do no wrong. Big beer, big sweetness, big dark color, big awesome. The cocoa and vanilla have run amok all over the place in this one. Savor it, slowly...

12oz. Interesting. Its like a session sour...kind of. Its breaded like a Belgian of some sort, with tiny hints of lemon zest sour between the biscuits. Pretty good for what it is actually, Id buy it again.

Bomber. The RIS from Stone was pretty much my favorite beer ever when I started geeking on craft beer back in 2005. It thinned out a bit over the years and many other breweries cropped up, but it is still one damn good beer. These variations theyre doing now however have revamped the RIS into further awesomeness. This is an excellent version. Being a chai snob as well, you can really taste the cardamom and clove throughout, as it blends with the RIS chocolate and burnt malts. So fucking good.
beer_name: Stone Imperial Russian Stout - Chai Spiced

review_blob: 375ml. Wow. This is one of those beers. Tart and effervescent. Light and bold. You can taste the barrel like youre licking it. The pinot notes are huge with sweet lemons, sugary almost, but so well done. Its bitter tart on the finish, it sticks. Its...so fucking dank!!

Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Otherwise known on their menu as Barrel OBitch, this is Bete Blanche in oak for 10 weeks. There was big wood hints up front, but ended up being kind of watery. Good flavors though.

On tap and in bombers many times in and around Seattle. This beauty pours a lovely golden blonde with a fluffy white head. The aroma off this guy is super Belgian yeasty with light fruit tones and bits of spices thrown about. The flavor continues this a bit with a solid carbonated body like a trippel, yet there is a bit more going on. Light grass notes amongst the forward hop and spice presence exist. Fairly sweet all the while...somehow this guy falls in between a Saison, a Trippel, and a Belgian Wit...good stuff!
beer_name: Elysian Bte Blanche Belgian Tripel (2011 and later)

review_blob: Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival and a few other times back then. Nice and up front Belgian sugary malts and hints of dark fruits on the nose and palate. Was usually pretty good!
Draft at the 2009 Great Elysian Beer Festival. Remember this being pretty light and very raspberry oriented. Bit of sweet malts and a tiny hop singe taboot.
12oz. Damn good crisp IPA here. Straightforward with a sharp citrus bite throughout. Dank and dry. Love the single hop stuffs!!
12oz. Syrupy root beer aroma. Tastes like root beer, drinks like root beer, is root beer with alcohol. Now I want to try the 18% version.
beer_name: Small Town Not Your Fathers Root Beer (5.9%)

review_blob: 12oz. Decent for what it is - a fairly light White IPA. Nothing much else to see here.

750ml. Another find of pure brilliance in a bottle. As much as there is going on here you can tell the levels of layers between the Belgian base beer, the excessive amount of hops tossed in, and a nice, light, barnyard funk from the bretts. Layered but blended so well. Mature and petite on the palate, but loud overall in general!
12oz and on tap. This is simply fantastic in every way from creation to follow through to palate. Lovely color, lovely nose, brilliant taste and idea. More like this please!
16oz can. Exactly what is it. Single IPA with enough going on it drinks well but isnt exciting.
beer_name: Golden Road Point the Way IPA

review_blob: Bomber. Nice creamy oaty offering here from Lagunitas. Lots of grain on the nose and palate, good combo with the spicey hopped up kick in the finish. Good, not great.

On tap at Chucks Hop Shop CD a few weeks back. Since when have I ever had a brew from De Molen that wasnt amazing? Oh yah, NEVER. This was the same. Huge and thick Impy Stout, what theyre known for, but with added flavors of cocoa, peppers, and salt. The salt was only detectable in the back end, but the cacao and chilis were swimming around your nose and palate like Heaven. Dank.

Tap at Tahoe Mountain Tap Room a month back. Aroma blasts you with a lovely bloody citrus canvas with hints of wet grass. Flavor is more blood orange and little hints of hay and wet pineapples. Little thin, but good.

Tap at Tahoe Mountain Tap Room a month back. Fucking phenomenal. Lightly sherry spiced nose with buried hints of sweet malts and light funk. Flavor is cherry and dark fruit doused in sherry blended in a barnyard with sour notes. Dank.
beer_name: Tahoe Mountain Rcolte Du Bois - Sherry

review_blob: Tap at Tahoe Mountain Tap Room a month back. Remember a fairly wet wheat aroma with a hint of sour. Wet on the palate as well. The sour is there, but could be more forward. Drinks really well and sessionable. Still pretty good.

Tap at Tahoe Mountain Tap Room a month back. Lightly spiced nose with hints of bretty barnyard and fruit. Cherries up front on the palate mixed with light funk and hints of the peppercorns. Damn good.
Tap at Tahoe Mountain Tap Room a month back. Slight funk filled Trappist style brew. Nice sweet hints of Earth and dark fruit. Pretty tasty.

22oz. This was absolutely fantastic. Nose of smoked salt, hints of buried hefe, honey, and funk. Soft at first on the tongue, then opens up into this beautiful world of perfectly smoked salty grainy honey coated goodness. Really.

12oz. Smells great, sounds great, but doesnt fully come through. They do say that they were going for light here though and that is right on. Nice vanillad coffee lingering notes in the finish. Refreshing almost. Could be louder but decent.
beer_name: Ballast Point Calm Before The Storm

review_blob: Bomber, yellow wax. Was surprised to see so many low ratings on this! Bad bottles? I knew right away from the nose on this beauty this would be a winner. Thick but polite hints of coconut cream, cocoa, vanilla, and roast on the nose. Big, but again polite body. Blasts of mixed chocolate/vanilla and coconut meat throughout. Sweet roast on the finish. Couldnt pick up on the nuts so much. SUPER creamy smooth. All in all a great beverage!

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Decent highly citrused offering here from Magic Hat. Grapefruit present enough on the nose and palate to make it more than your average IPA. Not too loud in any direction though.

A nice concept here. A saison with apple cider infused. The Cider notes are actually more profound than the saison buried beneath. Lightly tart, lightly dry, very drinkable. Overall a tasty beverage, but I could use a little bit louder notes in general.
Thick like jam. Huge berry nose, scents of apple throughout. Very sweet overall. If youre a dry cider person, this ones not for you.
beer_name: Blue Mountain Raspberry Hard Apple Cider

review_blob: WOW, this was fantastic. My fav hop brought up further notches by getting what seems to be its first single hop DIPA. Glorious tropical notes abound, I could drink this forever!

Absolutely loving this blood orange PA/IPA craze or fad going around right now. Lagunitas of course brings it proper with the perfect hop profile to fit the beautiful blast of citrus from the oranges. Excellent 6er beer.
Wow, look at all those ratings!! While this isnt a knock your socks off or anything brew, its one of very few American Wheats that is AWEOME.
